heir own ‘poetics of abridgement’. The concluding chapter advances an updated summary of Epicurus’ fragmentary "On Nature", interpreting his compendia not merely as sources for reconstructing the main treatise, but as texts with literary value in their own right. This monograph therefore provides the first complete presentation of Epicurean philosophical compendia, arguing for an interpretation of the rhetoric of philosophical texts while also being informed by metaliterary details afforded by other ancient sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Italian.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aAntike Textform. 4aEpikureismus. 4aEpitom. 4aKompendienliteratur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Textual Genres.  aEpicureanism.  aEpitome.  aPhilosophical Compendia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2021z9783110753813oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831107116910 cprintz978311071146240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311071158540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110711585423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110711585.jpg  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1b2021  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021